Acting on results with find and exec.

Find becomes genuinely powerful when you pair it with dash exec, which runs a command on each file it matches. There are two forms, and the difference matters. In the first form, you write dash exec, the command, a pair of curly braces, and then an escaped semicolon. The curly braces are replaced with each filename, and find runs the command once per file. That is simple but slow when there are many matches, because it starts a fresh process for every single file.

The second form ends with a plus sign instead of the semicolon. Find then gathers all the matches and passes them to the command together, running it just once or a few times. This is much faster, and you should prefer it unless you specifically need the command to run separately on each file. The classic good use is fixing permissions recursively: find all the directories and set them to one mode, then find all the regular files and set them to another. That is the correct way to apply directory and file permissions separately, avoiding the trap where a flat recursive change makes all your files executable.

Find also has a built-in delete action, which is faster and safer than calling remove through dash exec, good for clearing out old temporary files or empty directories. But be careful: always run the find without the delete first, to inspect exactly what would be removed. Finally, there is x-args, a separate tool that reads a list on standard input and turns it into command arguments, roughly like the plus form of dash exec but usable with any command that produces a list. When filenames might contain spaces or newlines, pair find's dash print-zero with x-args dash zero, which separate items with null characters instead of newlines and keep everything safe.
